I believe using "weakly typed" is more appropriate here.
Dynamic typing and weak typing are strictly speaking two different terms. "Dynamically typed" means that type checking only happens at runtime, not compile or design time, while "weakly typed" means that there's implicit type coercion.
To be clear, JS is both. But some languages are like Python: dynamic, but with no implicit type coercion.

Request to remove the semicolon from the return line of nums(a, b), as this question doesn't make much sense with it in place - it's built around the gotcha of the semicolon being missing. The semicolons were potentially auto-added by a linter due to the exact reason discussed in the answer, but in this case it's important to keep that ambiguity.
It might be worthwhile to remove the other semicolons in the function, as well (which would match the formatting of some of the translations, such as NL), but this is the minimum required change for this to make sense again.

Without the parentheses everything between the curly braces is considered a block statement.
In case we tried to "return" an object with just one property - the key would be interpreted as a label, the code would have been valid and indeed undefined would have been returned.
const getUser = user => { name: user.name } // always returns undefined
But if we try to "return" an object that has more than 1 property, SyntaxError gets thrown.
const getUser = user => { name: user.name, age: user.age } // SyntaxError
